A systematic analysis of 70 studies found that, in order to improve the situation of hand hygiene in lower-middle-income countries, there is effective community-based health and epidemic surveillance, while public marketing campaigns are less effective. One example of advocacy on hand-washing in schools is the United Nations Children's Fund's "Three Star Approach" approach: it promotes simple cost-effective measures in schools to encourage pupils to wash their hands using soap as well as other hygiene requirements.
